 A new government bringing change to one which has done well regarding economy and unemployment. I'm guessing the economy will go down, unemployment will go up. (Of course governments can skew unemployment by calling their own creation of government jobs beneficial to the economy.)

post_info.post_title: Australian government change...what will it bring to Australian's living conditions?

Yeah, 'cause the economy does so well when you've killed your ecosystem...

From what I have heard the Labour leader is a fiscal conservative, I doubt the economic polices of Australia will change much. The big difference might be foreign policy, the Labour Party opposed the Iraq. I expect that relations with the US might cool slightly. 
 
 Symbiote(an Aussie) might have a better handle on the result than me.

I don't expect large changes.
 
 The labor party has committed to withdrawing some of the Australian deployment from Iraq; far as I can tell they will be pulling out ~500 soldiers on the ground involved in policing and training, they leave behind the larger proportion of the deployment such as security for various officials over there and the naval deployment.
 
 They've also committed to (partially) rolling back the last round of employment deregulation which has been in effect for perhaps the last year.
 
 They've committed to budget surplus, the biggest problem with labor in the past has been their accumulation of an enormous national debt which over the last 11 years has been finally paid off. And they've committed to substantial tax cuts, similar to those put forward by the liberal party.
 
 Assuming the Primie Minister has good control over policy and the trade union XXXXXX that dream of crushing business aren't allowed much influence, I don't see any real problems.

The new Aussie premier in the UK has been likened to the unlamented Tony Blair.
 
 Just hope for Australia's sake he isn't like Teflon Tony, who by the way seems to have got out of the way just in time!

I don't really see the similarites from this hemisphere. Not that I kept up with Blair's politics much, but I thought he was largely reviled for taking Bushs' lead, whereas Rudd represents the opposite.
